answer:
We need to calculate the probability that Gimli flips more heads than Legolas.  This can be broken down into two cases: either Gimli flips exactly one more head, or Gimli flips two or more more heads.  Let us consider each of these cases separately.

\begin{align*}
\text{Case 1: Gimli flips exactly one more head.}\\
\text{The probability that Gimli flips exactly one more head than Legolas is the same as the probability that}\\
\text{Gimli flips 1005 heads and Legolas flips 1004 heads.  This can be calculated as follows:}\\
\binom{2009}{1005}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{1005}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{1004} = \frac{2009!}{1005!1004!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\text{Case 2: Gimli flips two or more more heads.}\\
\text{The probability that Gimli flips two or more more heads than Legolas is the same as the probability that}\\
\text{Gimli flips 1006 heads or more and Legolas flips 1004 heads or less.  This can be calculated as follows:}\\
\sum_{i=1006}^{2009}\binom{2009}{i}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{i}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009-i} = \sum_{i=1006}^{2009}\binom{2009}{i}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\text{Therefore, the probability that Gimli flips more heads than Legolas is}\\
\frac{2009!}{1005!1004!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}+\sum_{i=1006}^{2009}\binom{2009}{i}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\text{This can be simplified as follows:}\\
\frac{2009!}{1005!1004!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}+\sum_{i=0}^{2009}\binom{2009}{i}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}-\frac{2008!}{1004!1004!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}\\
=\left[\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}\sum_{i=0}^{2009}\binom{2009}{i}-\frac{2008!}{1004!1004!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}\right]\\
=\left[\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}(2^{2009})-\frac{2008!}{1004!1004!}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^{2009}\right]\\
=\frac{1}{2}.
\end{align*}

\boxed{\frac{1}{2}}
Final Answer: The final answer is \frac{1}{2}. I hope it is correct.

