question:
If $a,b,c$ are positive integers less than $13$ such that \begin{align*}
2ab+bc+ca&\equiv 0\pmod{13}\\
ab+2bc+ca&\equiv 6abc\pmod{13}\\
ab+bc+2ca&\equiv 8abc\pmod {13}
\end{align*}then determine the remainder when $a+b+c$ is divided by $13$.

answer:
We subtract the first equation from the second and third to get
\begin{align*}
ca+bc-ca&\equiv 6abc-8abc\pmod{13}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad bc&\equiv 2abc\pmod{13}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad b&\equiv 2a\pmod{13}
\end{align*}
We can plug this into the first equation to get
\begin{align*}
2a^2+2ac+c&\equiv 0\pmod{13}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad a^2+ac+c&\equiv 0\pmod{13}
\end{align*}
We can now subtract the first equation from the second to get
\begin{align*}
ab+bc+ca&\equiv 6abc\pmod{13}\\
ab+bc+ca&\equiv 0\pmod{13}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad ab&\equiv 0\pmod{13}
\end{align*}
Since $a$ is a positive integer less than $13$, we must have $a\equiv 0\pmod{13}$ or $a\equiv 12\pmod{13}$.  If $a\equiv 0\pmod{13}$, then we would have $b\equiv 0\pmod{13}$, but then we would have $ab\equiv 0\pmod{13}$ and $ab+bc+ca\equiv 0\pmod{13}$, which would imply $bc+ca\equiv 0\pmod{13}$, which would imply $b+c\equiv 0\pmod{13}$, but then we would have $a+b+c\equiv 0\pmod{13}$, which is a contradiction.  Therefore, we must have $a\equiv 12\pmod{13}$.  This would give us $b\equiv 2\pmod{13}$ and $c\equiv 1\pmod{13}$.  Then $a+b+c\equiv 12+2+1\equiv \boxed{5}\pmod{13}$.
Final Answer: The final answer is 5. I hope it is correct.

