Let the four angles be $x-d, x, x+d, x+3d$ for some $d$.  The sum of the interior angles of a quadrilateral is $360^{\circ}$, so
\begin{align*}
x-d+x+x+d+x+3d&=360\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 4x+3d&=360\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 4x&=360-3d.
\end{align*}
The largest angle is $x+3d$, which is $129^{\circ}$, so $x+3d=129$.  We can substitute $x=360-3d-129=211-3d$ into this equation to get
\begin{align*}
211-3d+3d&=129\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 211&=129+3d\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3d&=211-129=82\\
\Rightarrow\qquad d&=82/3.
\end{align*}
Now we can substitute $d=82/3$ into $4x=360-3d$ to get
\begin{align*}
4x&=360-3\cdot\frac{82}{3}=360-82=278\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=278/4=69.5.
\end{align*}
The second largest angle is $x+d=69.5+82/3=\boxed{103}$.
Final Answer: The final answer is 103. I hope it is correct.

