The sum of an infinite geometric series with first term $a$ and common ratio $r$ is $S = \frac{a}{1-r}.$ Therefore, $S = \frac{a}{1-b}.$ We are also given that $S = 1/S,$ so

$$\frac{a}{1-b} = \frac{1}{S}.$$We can solve for $S$: \begin{align*}
\frac{a}{1-b} &= \frac{1}{S}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad S &= \frac{1}{a/(1-b)} = \frac{1-b}{a}.
\end{align*}Now, we can solve for $a+b$: \begin{align*}
S &= \frac{1-b}{a}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad a &= \frac{1-b}{S}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad a+b &= \frac{1-b}{S}+b\\
&= \frac{1-b}{1/b}+b\\
&= 1 + (b-b)\\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}
