We have that
\begin{align*}
-24+7i&=r(\cos\theta+i\sin\theta)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -24&=r\cos\theta\\
7&=r\sin\theta
\end{align*}
Squaring both sides of the second equation, we get
\begin{align*}
49&=r^2\sin^2\theta\\
\Rightarrow\qquad r^2&=\frac{49}{\sin^2\theta}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad r&=\frac{7}{\sin\theta}
\end{align*}
Substituting into the first equation, we get
\begin{align*}
-24&=\frac{7\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -24\sin\theta&=7\cos\theta\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 7\cos\theta&=-24\sin\theta\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\cos\theta&=-\frac{24}{7}\sin\theta
\end{align*}
We can use the identity $\sin^2\theta+\cos^2\theta=1$ to find $\sin\theta$ in terms of $\cos\theta$:
\begin{align*}
\sin^2\theta+\cos^2\theta&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\sin^2\theta+(-\frac{24}{7}\sin\theta)^2&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\sin^2\theta+\frac{576}{49}\sin^2\theta&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\frac{625}{49}\sin^2\theta&=1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\sin^2\theta&=\frac{49}{625}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad\sin\theta&=\frac{7}{25}
\end{align*}
Now, we can substitute this into the equation $\cos\theta=-\frac{24}{7}\sin\theta$:
\begin{align*}
\cos\theta&=-\frac{24}{7}\sin\theta\\
&=-\frac{24}{7}\cdot\frac{7}{25}\\
&=\boxed{-\frac{24}{25}}
\end{align*}
